{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"05b20217-2d8e-49f4-b33c-1341a60e9f52","content":"**Not quite ready.** Here are the issues:\n\n### 🔴 Functional Bug\n- **`Framework` symbol missing `replaces`** — The parameter is defined but never substitutes anything in source files. You need `\"replaces\": \"net9.0\"` (or whatever placeholder is in your `.csproj`) so the chosen framework actually gets applied.\n\n### 🟡 Recommended for NuGet Publishing\n| Missing Field | Why It Matters |\n|---|---|\n| `$schema` | Enables validation & editor IntelliSense (`http://json.schemastore.org/template`) |\n| `groupIdentity` | Groups related templates in NuGet; best practice for discoverability |\n| `preferNameDirectory` | Should be `true` for project templates so `dotnet new` creates a subfolder |\n| `defaultName` | Fallback project name when the user doesn't pass `--name` |\n\n### ✅ Looks Good\n- `identity`, `shortName`, `name`, `author` — all present\n- `classifications` and `tags` are well-formed\n- `sourceName` is set for name replacement\n\n**Minimum fix** to unblock publishing — add `replaces` to the Framework symbol:\n\n```json\n\"Framework\": {\n  \"type\": \"parameter\",\n  \"datatype\": \"choice\",\n  \"defaultValue\": \"net9.0\",\n  \"replaces\": \"net9.0\",\n  ...\n}\n```\n\nWant me to apply these fixes?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"affa5869-1a5d-44bf-8c50-bc1a3d3b5963","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Let me review this template.json for NuGet publishing readiness. I'll check against the .NET template engine schema requirements.\n\nIssues I can identify:\n\n1. **Missing `$schema`** — Not strictly required, but strongly recommended for validation and editor support. The standard value is `http://json.schemastore.org/template`.\n\n2. **Missing `groupIdentity`** — Recommended for NuGet packages, especially if you plan to have multiple related templates. Not strictly required but best practice.\n\n3. **Missing `precedence`** — Useful when multiple versions of a template exist. Not required for a first publish.\n\n\n4. **Missing `preferNameDirectory`** — Optional, but commonly set for project templates.\n\n5. **Missing `defaultName`** — Optional, provides a default project name if the user doesn't specify one.\n\nThe core template properties look solid—`sourceName`, `identity`, `shortName`, `author`, `classifications`, and `tags` are all present and properly configured. I'm now examining the `Framework` symbol to see if it's correctly defined for the template engine.\n\nThe `Framework` symbol is missing a `replaces` property, which means selecting a framework won't actually substitute anything in the generated files—that's a functional bug. Beyond that, I'm also noticing the template lacks a `$schema` for validation, no `groupIdentity` for NuGet best practices, and those optional but recommended fields like `preferNameDirectory` and `defaultName`. The `sources` section could also benefit from explicit `exclude` patterns to avoid copying unnecessary files.","outputTokens":859,"requestId":"401D:913B3:4906E4:556FFA:69F00632"},"id":"f61a4b41-feb3-415d-bfd9-aae797eb6076","timestamp":"2026-04-28T00:58:45.092Z","parentId":"84ef1b3f-334a-4041-84ab-b1d9e6702da0"}
